1. 28. Arminium, a Latin form of ‘ Hermann.’. The character and career of this prince are summed up in 2. 88, and other relatives of his are mentioned in c, 57, 5; 58, 9; 60, 1; 2. 9, 2. His leadership of the Cheruscans and other German tribes began with the rising against Varus3 at which time he was but twenty-five years old (2. 88, 4), but had already served with the Roman armies (2. 10, 3), and, according to Velleius, had received the Roman citizenship and even equestrian rank.

l. 4. gener invisus inimici soceri. The two last words are best taken as genit. sing, and explained by distinguishing ‘invisus' from ‘inimici;’ the meaning being that Arminius, already at enmity with Segestes on public grounds, was additionally hateful to him from the way in which he became his son-in-law. This is expanded in the next sentence (‘quaeque . . . erant’), where ‘ apud infensos' answers to ‘ inimici‚' and ‘ incitamenta irarum’ to ‘ invisus.'
